column1: Who will win Chile’s 2017 presidential election?

column11: The Chilean presidential election is scheduled for 19 November 2017, with a run-off scheduled for 17 December 2017 if no candidate wins a majority of the votes in the first round (Prensa Latina, US News & World Report, Santiago Times). Sebastian Pinera won Chile's 2017 presidential election (Latin American News Agency). This question closed as "c) Sebastian Pinera." See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated.

column6: Polls are banned in the weeks ahead of the election but analysts say that based on the last polls released and trends seen, it appears the race is now up for grabs.
Final forecast up

Looked at Polling data listed by Cadem on Wikipedia. Piñera consistently ahead but just barely. With the margin of error it is a toss up. However, there is some expectation that young voters are not inspired by either candidate and will sit out the election. This favors Piñera.

The wind seems to be blowing in favor of the Chilean right. The country’s left-wing parties are fragmented. Its current socialist government, headed by Michelle Bachelet, is deeply unpopular. And a few days before the runoff election on Sunday to choose the country’s next leader, the center-right candidate, Sebastián Piñera, who won the first round of voting, on November 19, is polling three to five points ahead of his opponent, the independent senator Alejandro Guillier.

The Broad Front has not formally endorsed any candidate in the second round, but former candidate Beatriz Sanchez announced that her “vote is against Sebastian Piñera,” and therefore “for Alejandro Guillier.”

If Guillier got more than 85% of the Sanchez' votes that were cast in round 1, he might be able to beat Piñera based on voter preferences outlined in Criteria Research. Those preferences from Dec 1 opinion research indicated 77% of Sanchez votes may be cast for Guillier. This was before Sanchez indicated she personally would vote for Guillier. Jumping to 85% with all other assumptions staying the same, Piñera could beat Guillier by less than 1% with turnout expected to be lower than first round. I'm not sure I believe 85% as endorsements from the left have been tepid. Staying with current forecast and tracking news for signs of momentum.

Beatriz Sanchez, the flagbearer for the hard-left Frente Amplio coalition, said Pinera’s suggestion that ballots had been tampered with in the first-round election had changed her mind about staying quiet on whom she would vote for in the run-off.
Difficult to find current situation. Polling could be wrong. Guess it left will split and more Conservative Piñera wins.

With the rise of the new Chilean left the result is more uncertain than some may think. The central question is if Beatriz Sanchez and her movement of 13 (!) different groups will endorse Alejandro Guillier and provide the necessary votes to give him a realistic chance. It's probable that already some of her voters will vote for Gullier but that won't be enough to present a real challenge for Pinera. Some groups have already decided to back Gullier while some have denied support. At the moment, however, Pinera is most likely the next president of Chile.

Chile election: Conservative Piñera to face Socialist Guillier in run-off Mr Guillier won 22.7% of the vote. He is a former journalist and the candidate from Ms Bachelet's left-wing Nueva Mayoría coalition. Let's see the second round on 17 December.
The candidate with momentum, Sanchez, has been eliminated, and the left vote is therefore divided. Pinera has been ahead in polling since the first round.

The biggest political polling institute in Chile, Cadem has published its first post-election study, which measured the likely results of the second round of the presidential election happening on the 17th December.

If you include just votes won by these two candidates its a 62-38% split. That moves up to ~75% if you include the votes almost guaranteed from Kast supporters. Guillier is likely to pick up some votes from the left himself which makes me nudge his chance up a bit. The largest polling institute in Chile has it pretty close but they were way off in the first round and have admitted they haven't had time to update their model so I'm not reading too much into that.

Based on analysis of polling of first round election, Beatriz Sanchez beat all expectations. Overall turnout in the second round is expected to be less (42%) than the first round (46.6%). This also happened in 2013, the first election where voting became voluntary.

Bachelet's government is perceived as ineffective, enhancing the center-right chances.
Pinera seems to be holding onto his solid but not insurmountable lead.

Chileans seem to be relatively disillusioned, believing that the path they are on will remain constant regardless of who sits in the presidential chair. Sebastian Pinera has, a few things working towards his favor. He has a proven track record (both positives and negatives), he's a wealthy business man who proposes to cut government spending and improve the economy. In interviews, Pinera also seems to carry himself with more digestible and "likeable" aura of self confidence that copmliments his character and political strengths. However, Alejandro Guillier is likely to come in 2nd and it is too soon to predict where the country will lean in the December run off election.
Pinera's party will get out the vote which will be determining factor since voting is no longer mandatory.

Estimated First Round to November 03: Sebastián Piñera 45%, Alejandro Guillier 23%, Beatriz Sánchez 14%, Carolina Goic 6%, José Antonio Kast 6%, Marco Enríquez Ominami 5%, Alejandro Navarro 0.5% and Eduardo Artés 0.5%.
Why do people think/ believe/ hope across the democracies of this globe, that billionaires will do the best fro them and the country?

I am rethinking all the predictions and the forecasts in the wake of the rebirth of populism? The mood of the voters is short sighted and very shaky, rumors and manipulations can result in big and unexpected changes. I specifically think of the vulnerability of an election system as is in place in Chile. from the first to the second electoral round, there is no such thing as a "sure" winner. for the second round everything is open again, it is a question of mobilization.

I know my intuition on elections is terrible, so I'll follow @shivadiva's explanation and evaluation of probabilities at https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/592165 plus his/her final adjustment that same day. I have more faith in the judgment of another forecaster when the forecaster makes several adjustments soon after considering the data.

Not convinced the far left would compromise in order to support a center left candidate in the runoff.

Voters in Chile are ready for a change in the party running the country. Mr. Pinera has the backing of the business establishment and a vast personal fortune. It is hard to imagine his advantages not being enough to win. Only an upset of the Trump type would open the door for Guillier. He is an anti establishment candidate and if a "vote for change" or "drain the swamp" took hold among the electorate it is possible he could do the upset. Certainly his politics are not that of Trump but his message sounds familiar to what won for Trump.
Too stable to shake things up.

Sebastian Pinera has been able to increase support from 40% to 43% over the past months and Alejandro Guillier is quite far behind (but still the closest) with 20%. Despite Pinera in the lead, there is a story here in Chile that the electorate is not totally convinced which direction the country should take. Pinera would certainly be a very business oriented persident who runs the country more like a firm.

Most recent poll (http://www.euronews.com/2017/10/03/chiles-pinera-would-win-44-pct-in-presidential-first-round-pollster) suggestst that Guillier and Pinera enter the second round and Sanchez is likely to be eliminated for the run-off. This might need adjustment when more information becomes available.
PIggybacking on other forecasters, waiting for more info.

Latest poll has Pinera at 44%, Guillier at 30%, Sanchez at 11%. Pinera is conservative, Gullier is center-left. Sanchez and the other candidates in the election are on the left wing of the political spectrum. Most of their voters will probably vote for Guillier in a run-off. Pinera has an advantage, but it's not decisive.
Sanchez is certain to be eliminated. That will mean his voters will consolidate with Guillier, who may beat Pinera in a repeat of the upset election in Peru. Fuji was the GJ favourite.

C.R. polls indicate 2nd round could be close. Cadem polls list Pinera with 10% leads against both Guillier and Sanchez in the 2nd round. Any upset will depend on effective consolidation of the opposition to Pinera.

Pinera current has a comfortable lead in the polls, around twice that of his serious opponents. But he's not at fifty so there will most likely be a runoff and in that case I think Guillier rather than Sanchez is more likely to win as he is the more moderate centrist candidate.
